ns, both locally and nationally. Employing Lave and Wenger's concept of "communities of practice" as a framework, this book emphasizes the variety of processes by which new citizens acquire the civic and leadership skills that help them to move from peripheral positions to more central roles in American society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEast Indian AmericansxPolitical activityzTexas. 0aEast Indian AmericanszTexasxSocieties, etc. 0aImmigrantsxPolitical activityzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocieties, etc.vCase studies. 0aVietnamese AmericansxPolitical activityzTexas. 0aVietnamese AmericanszTexasxSocieties, etc. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aReed-Danahay, Deborah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477898540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778985423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778985.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles